  "doi": "10.1016/j.omto.2020.07.008",
  "title": "Molecular Rules Underpinning Enhanced Affinity Binding of Human T Cell Receptors Engineered for Immunotherapy.",
  "journal": "Molecular therapy oncolytics",
  "year": 2020,
  "authors": "Crean RM, MacLachlan BJ, Madura F, Whalley T, Rizkallah PJ, Holland CJ, McMurran C, Harper S, Godkin A, Sewell AK, Pudney CR, van der Kamp MW, Cole DK."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study examined engineered T cell receptors (TCRs) designed to bind cancer-associated peptide\u2013MHC-I complexes with dramatically higher affinity than their natural counterparts, comparing crystal structures of enhanced-affinity variants with wild-type precursors and performing molecular dynamics simulations to dissect binding mechanisms. The analysis revealed that million-fold affinity improvements can be achieved without fundamentally altering the native TCR\u2013pHLA binding geometry, instead arising from subtle interface modifications\u2014particularly the introduction of buried hydrophobic residues\u2014whose energetic contributions vary substantially across individual TCRs and often involve additive or allosteric effects beyond the mutated positions. These findings provide molecular principles for rational design of engineered TCRs as immunotherapeutic agents for cancer, addressing a major limitation of natural TCRs, which recognize tumor epitopes with insufficient binding strength to mount effective anti-tumor responses.",
